	<section class="section section-cream">
		<div class="blog-post reveal">
			<div class="blog-post-meta">
				<p class="meta-info">Published April 1, 2026 · By the Sula Catering Team</p>
			</div>

			<p>Every <a href="/weddings">South Asian wedding in Vancouver</a> has a moment when chai matters — when the elders settle into a quiet corner after the ceremony, when the bride's parents need a pause before the reception, when the late-night dancing finally winds down and someone asks for "just one more cup." Coffee has its own moments: the early morning getting-ready hours, the afternoon mehndi, the long reception when guests need a second wind. The mistake is choosing one over the other.</p>

			<h2>Why <em>Chai</em> Belongs</h2>
			<p>For South Asian families, chai isn't a beverage — it's a ritual. It's how the day begins. It's how you welcome someone into your home. It's the small punctuation between every meaningful moment.</p>
			<p>A live masala chai station at your wedding does something subtle and powerful: it tells your elders, your aunties, your visiting relatives that this part of the celebration was designed for them. It's a small detail with a big emotional payoff.</p>

			<h2>What a Live Chai Bar <em>Actually Is</em></h2>
			<p>At Sula, we set up copper urns and brew chai fresh on-site through the event. Whole spices: cardamom, ginger, fennel, black pepper, cinnamon. Loose-leaf Assam tea simmered with milk and sugar. Served in small ceramic cups or paper cups depending on the venue.</p>
			<p>We can run a chai bar for 50 guests or 500. The setup scales beautifully and the cost per guest is genuinely modest.</p>

			<h2>Why <em>Coffee</em> Also Belongs</h2>
			<p>Half your wedding guests grew up here. Or they're working professionals who run on espresso. Or they're Gen Z and the only "tea" they drink is matcha. A coffee bar tells them they're part of the party too.</p>
			<p>For mehndi mornings, getting-ready hours, and any event that starts before noon, a barista-led coffee station is essential. Espresso, lattes, cortados, drip — full service through <a href="/cafe-catering">Sula Café</a>.</p>

			<h2>When to Run <em>Each</em></h2>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>Mehndi morning:</strong> coffee bar is the priority, with chai as the secondary option</li>
				<li><strong>Sangeet evening:</strong> chai bar opens after dinner, runs until the last guest leaves</li>
				<li><strong>Ceremony day morning:</strong> coffee for the bridal party, chai for arriving family</li>
				<li><strong>Reception:</strong> coffee bar near the dessert station, chai bar near the lounge area</li>
				<li><strong>After-party:</strong> chai is the universal closer — comforting, grounding, slow</li>
			</ul>

			<h2>Pair with the <em>Right Sweets</em></h2>
			<p>A chai or coffee bar without sweets is a missed opportunity. We pair our beverage stations with fresh-baked Indian pastries: masala biscuits, koliyada, cardamom shortbread. For coffee, croissants and seasonal cakes. For chai, salty biscuits and gulab jamun.</p>

			<h2>The Cost <em>Reality</em></h2>
			<p>Many couples assume a live beverage station is a luxury add-on. The reality: chai and coffee bars typically run $4-$8 per guest depending on duration and styling. For a 250-guest wedding, that's a small line item with disproportionate emotional impact.</p>

			<h2>Bring the Café to Your <em>Wedding</em></h2>
			<p>Sula Café was built around morning rituals and slow conversations. We bring all of that — the copper urns, the espresso machine, the fresh pastries, the warmth — to weddings, <a href="/private-parties">private parties</a>, and corporate events across Vancouver.</p>

			<h2>Final Thoughts</h2>
			<p>The food at your wedding will be remembered. So will the chai. Don't choose one beverage tradition over the other — honour both. <a href="https://sulaindianrestaurant.com/request-a-quote/">Request a quote</a> and our café team will design a beverage program that fits every part of your celebration.</p>

